2.4 Find out the numeric range of the input. Do we need to rescale the input?¶

In [9]:
print("Numeric range of training input is", format(train_images.max() - train_images.min()))
print("Numeric range of test input is", format(test_images.max() - test_images.min()))

Numeric range of training input is 255
Numeric range of test input is 255

If we input values to neural network which are much larger than the initial values taken by the weights of a network or data that is heterogeneous (for example, data where one feature is in the range 0–1 and another is in the range 100–200). Then, this will trigger large gradient updates that will prevent the network from converging. To make learning easier for the network, we should take small values (prefereably in 0-1 range) and this range should be homogenous for values in all features. We have grey scale image as input, thus range of values will be between 0-255 (black - white) which is heterogenous. Thus, we need to rescale the input.

2.5 In our problem, what are the shapes of input tensors and target tensors? Do you need to reshape the input?¶

In [10]:
print("Shape of Training input tenshors:{}\nShape of Test input tenshors:{}".format(tf.shape(train_images),tf.shape(test_images)))
print("Rank of training input is",format(tf.rank(train_images)))
print("Rank of test input is",format(tf.rank(test_images)))

Shape of Training input tenshors:[60000    28    28]
Shape of Test input tenshors:[10000    28    28]
Rank of training input is 3
Rank of test input is 3

Images typically have three dimensions namely; height, weight, and color depth. Data is of grey scale image which has a single color channel, thus it can be stored in 2D tensors. Also, dense layers are used in the network to extract representation out of the data. As name suggests these layers are densely connected or full connected and if the input has rank greater than 2, then it needs to be flattened i.e. reshape to 2D. Thus, we need to reshape the input.

Task 3 Construct an input pipeline¶

3.1 Exploring data¶

In [0]:
#Function to check balance (frequency) of the data
def label_frequency(data):
  #Converting labels into dataframe
  df_data = pd.DataFrame(data)
  #Counting frequency of each label
  label_freq = df_data[0].value_counts()
  #Total number of samples
  total_sample = len(df_data)

  # Count the number of items in each class
  for i in range(len(label_freq)):
    label = class_names[label_freq.index[i]]
    label_code = label_freq.index[i]
    count = label_freq.values[i]
    percent = (count / total_sample) * 100
    print("{:<20s}: {}:  {} or {}%".format(label, label_code, count, percent))

3.2 Pre-processing data¶

In [11]:
#Reshaping training and test images
train_images = train_images.reshape((60000, 28 * 28))
train_images = train_images.astype('float32') / 255

test_images = test_images.reshape((10000, 28 * 28))
test_images = test_images.astype('float32') / 255

#1-hot-coding for labels
train_labels = to_categorical(train_labels)
test_labels = to_categorical(test_labels)

print("Training shape{}\nTest data shape{}".format((train_images.shape),(test_images.shape)))
print("\nUnique training labels{}\nUnique test labels{}".format((np.unique(train_labels)),(np.unique(test_labels))))

Training shape(60000, 784)
Test data shape(10000, 784)

Unique training labels[0. 1.]
Unique test labels[0. 1.]

3.3 Creating training, validation, test data and tf.data pipeline¶

In [12]:
#Splitting training data into training and validation dataset
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
X_train, X_val, Y_train, Y_val = train_test_split(train_images, train_labels, test_size = 0.2, random_state = 12345)

print("Validation images shape", format(X_val.shape))
print("Validation labels shape", format(Y_val.shape))
print("Training images shape", format(X_train.shape))
print("Training labels shape", format(Y_train.shape))

Validation images shape (12000, 784)
Validation labels shape (12000, 10)
Training images shape (48000, 784)
Training labels shape (48000, 10)
In [0]:
#Constructing tensorflow input pipeline 
train_dataset = tf.data.Dataset.from_tensor_slices((X_train, Y_train))
train_dataset = train_dataset.shuffle(buffer_size=512, seed=14).batch(512)

test_dataset = tf.data.Dataset.from_tensor_slices((test_images, test_labels))
test_dataset = test_dataset.batch(512)

val_dataset = tf.data.Dataset.from_tensor_slices((X_val, Y_val))
val_dataset = val_dataset.batch(512)

Task 4 Construct a deep forward neural network¶

4.1 Setting up a model for training¶

Output layer:¶

1. We have 10 output nodes as we have converted labels in categorical variable using 1-hot-coding.¶
2. We have used softmax activation function which will provide probability over 10 nodes (i.e. over 0's and 1's) summing to 1.¶

Hidden layer:¶

1. Two hidden layers with 256 nodes and relu activation each are created. Number of hidden layers and nodes are selected arbiteraly to start with. Relu activation function is used as it considers zero for negative inputs, but pixels does not have negative input and is efficient than sigmoid and tanh function.¶

Input layer:¶

1. Input layer unit's is 784 and input size is 28*28¶
a) Loss function used is categorical_crossentropy as label is a multiclass variable with 1-hot-coding. With integer coding, we could have used sparse categorical_crossentropy.¶
b) Accuracy metrics is used as we need to maximize accuracy whilst minimizing loss function.¶
c) RMSProp optimizer is used as which has better convergence speed and quality.¶
In [0]:
import datetime
#Building architect of the network
model = models.Sequential()
model.add(layers.Dense(256, activation='relu',input_shape=[28*28]))
model.add(layers.Dense(256, activation='relu'))
model.add(layers.Dense(10, activation='softmax'))

#Creating log directory and TensorBoard
log_dir = "logs/fit/" + datetime.datetime.now().strftime("%Y%m%d-%H%M%S")
tensorboard = tf.keras.callbacks.TensorBoard(log_dir=log_dir, histogram_freq=1)
In [0]:
#Creating model compiler
model.compile(optimizer=optimizers.RMSprop(lr=0.001),
              loss='categorical_crossentropy',
              metrics=['accuracy'])

#Model Structure using summary()

                    epochs = 1000,
                    validation_data=val_dataset,
                    callbacks=[tensorboard])

#Evaluating model over training and validation dataset
acc = history.history['accuracy']
val_acc = history.history['val_accuracy']
loss = history.history['loss']
val_loss = history.history['val_loss']

print("Average training accuracy across all epochs is",format(round(sum(acc)/len(acc),4)))
print("Average validation accuracy across all epochs is",format(round(sum(val_acc)/len(val_acc),4)))


#Plotting training and validation loss with number of epochs
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 10))
epochs = range(1, len(loss) + 1)
plt.plot(epochs, loss, 'bo', label='Training loss')
plt.plot(epochs, val_loss, 'b', label='Validation loss', color = 'red')
plt.title('Training and validation loss')
plt.xlabel('Epochs')
plt.ylabel('Loss')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

Average training accuracy across all epochs is 0.9924
Average validation accuracy across all epochs is 0.8998

1.Overfitting or underfitting¶

In loss vs epochs graph we can see that validation loss has increased continuously till 4 and training loss reduced constantly till ~zero. In accuracy vs epochs graph we can see that validation accuracy has been constant around 90% whereas training accuracy started below validation accuracy but reached closed to 100% in 200 epochs. Average training accuracy is 99% and validation accuracy is 90%. Based on these evidences we can say that model is overfitting. Probable reasons might be data is too noisy which has been identified by the model for training data and/or model is overly complex with too many parameters.

2. Epoch at which overfitting occurred¶

Overfitting occurred approximately between 70-80 epochs.

4.3 Check the convergence through gradient using TensorBoard¶

In [18]:
#Launching tensorboard
%reload_ext tensorboard
%tensorboard --logdir logs/fit

Output hidden; open in https://colab.research.google.com to view.
1.Do you see vanishing or exploding gradients?¶

There is vanishing gradient problem as per histogram of weights When the gradient is 0, this implies that the weights do not update. When the weights do not update, the distribution plots will be the same. So as a heuristic, if you see that the distribution plots remain the same, you know the update was small (possibly even 0). Also, from loss and accuracy plots we can infer that model had premature convergence, i.e. continued training does not result in any further improvement. This happens when weight does not changes i.e. gradient is vanishing.

2.Use the gradient norm to check if the training has converged to a local minimum.¶

1 Trial model - Reduced model¶

Since model is overfitting which might be due to complex model. Thus, in first trial model, we will simplify the model by reducing one hidden layer and reduce units to 128.

In [0]:
trial_01 = models.Sequential()

              loss='categorical_crossentropy',

#Evaluating model over training and validation dataset
acc = history_trial_01.history['accuracy']
val_acc = history_trial_01.history['val_accuracy']
loss = history_trial_01.history['loss']
val_loss = history_trial_01.history['val_loss']

print("Average training accuracy across all epochs is",format(round(sum(acc)/len(acc),4)))
print("Average validation accuracy across all epochs is",format(round(sum(val_acc)/len(val_acc),4)))


#Plotting training and validation loss with number of epochs
plt.figure(figsize=(5, 5))
epochs = range(1, len(loss) + 1)
plt.plot(epochs, loss, 'bo', label='Training loss')
plt.plot(epochs, val_loss, 'b', label='Validation loss', color = 'red')
plt.title('Training and validation loss')
plt.xlabel('Epochs')
plt.ylabel('Loss')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

#Plotting training and validation accuracy with number of epochs
plt.figure(figsize=(5, 5))
epochs = range(1, len(acc) + 1)
plt.plot(epochs, acc, 'bo', label='Training accuracy')
plt.plot(epochs, val_acc, 'b', label='Validation accuracy', color = 'red')
plt.title('Training and validation accuracy')
plt.xlabel('Epochs')
plt.ylabel('Accruacy')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

Average training accuracy across all epochs is 0.9877
Average validation accuracy across all epochs is 0.8944

#Evaluating model over training and validation dataset
acc = history_trial_02.history['accuracy']
val_acc = history_trial_02.history['val_accuracy']
loss = history_trial_02.history['loss']
val_loss = history_trial_02.history['val_loss']

print("Average training accuracy across all epochs is",format(round(sum(acc)/len(acc),4)))
print("Average validation accuracy across all epochs is",format(round(sum(val_acc)/len(val_acc),4)))


#Plotting training and validation loss with number of epochs
plt.figure(figsize=(5, 5))
epochs = range(1, len(loss) + 1)
plt.plot(epochs, loss, 'bo', label='Training loss')
plt.plot(epochs, val_loss, 'b', label='Validation loss', color = 'red')
plt.title('Training and validation loss')
plt.xlabel('Epochs')
plt.ylabel('Loss')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

#Plotting training and validation accuracy with number of epochs
plt.figure(figsize=(5, 5))
epochs = range(1, len(acc) + 1)
plt.plot(epochs, acc, 'bo', label='Training accuracy')
plt.plot(epochs, val_acc, 'b', label='Validation accuracy', color = 'red')
plt.title('Training and validation accuracy')
plt.xlabel('Epochs')
plt.ylabel('Accruacy')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

Average training accuracy across all epochs is 0.9906
Average validation accuracy across all epochs is 0.8781

#Evaluating model over training and validation dataset
acc = history_trial_03.history['accuracy']
val_acc = history_trial_03.history['val_accuracy']
loss = history_trial_03.history['loss']
val_loss = history_trial_03.history['val_loss']

print("Average training accuracy across all epochs is",format(round(sum(acc)/len(acc),4)))
print("Average validation accuracy across all epochs is",format(round(sum(val_acc)/len(val_acc),4)))


#Plotting training and validation loss with number of epochs
plt.figure(figsize=(5, 5))
epochs = range(1, len(loss) + 1)
plt.plot(epochs, loss, 'bo', label='Training loss')
plt.plot(epochs, val_loss, 'b', label='Validation loss', color = 'red')
plt.title('Training and validation loss')
plt.xlabel('Epochs')
plt.ylabel('Loss')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

#Evaluating model over training and validation dataset
acc = history_trial_04.history['accuracy']
val_acc = history_trial_04.history['val_accuracy']
loss = history_trial_04.history['loss']
val_loss = history_trial_04.history['val_loss']

print("Average training accuracy across all epochs is",format(round(sum(acc)/len(acc),4)))
print("Average validation accuracy across all epochs is",format(round(sum(val_acc)/len(val_acc),4)))


#Plotting training and validation loss with number of epochs
plt.figure(figsize=(5, 5))
epochs = range(1, len(loss) + 1)
plt.plot(epochs, loss, 'bo', label='Training loss')
plt.plot(epochs, val_loss, 'b', label='Validation loss', color = 'red')
plt.title('Training and validation loss')
plt.xlabel('Epochs')
plt.ylabel('Loss')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

#Plotting training and validation accuracy with number of epochs
plt.figure(figsize=(5, 5))
epochs = range(1, len(acc) + 1)
plt.plot(epochs, acc, 'bo', label='Training accuracy')
plt.plot(epochs, val_acc, 'b', label='Validation accuracy', color = 'red')
plt.title('Training and validation accuracy')
plt.xlabel('Epochs')
plt.ylabel('Accruacy')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

Average training accuracy across all epochs is 0.9323
Average validation accuracy across all epochs is 0.8852

In [0]:
#Evaluating model over training and validation dataset
acc = history_trial_05.history['accuracy']
val_acc = history_trial_05.history['val_accuracy']
loss = history_trial_05.history['loss']
val_loss = history_trial_05.history['val_loss']

print("Average training accuracy across all epochs is",format(round(sum(acc)/len(acc),4)))
print("Average validation accuracy across all epochs is",format(round(sum(val_acc)/len(val_acc),4)))


#Plotting training and validation loss with number of epochs
plt.figure(figsize=(5, 5))
epochs = range(1, len(loss) + 1)
plt.plot(epochs, loss, 'bo', label='Training loss')
plt.plot(epochs, val_loss, 'b', label='Validation loss', color = 'red')
plt.title('Training and validation loss')
plt.xlabel('Epochs')
plt.ylabel('Loss')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

#Plotting training and validation accuracy with number of epochs
plt.figure(figsize=(5, 5))
epochs = range(1, len(acc) + 1)
plt.plot(epochs, acc, 'bo', label='Training accuracy')
plt.plot(epochs, val_acc, 'b', label='Validation accuracy', color = 'red')
plt.title('Training and validation accuracy')
plt.xlabel('Epochs')
plt.ylabel('Accruacy')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

Average training accuracy across all epochs is 0.9558
Average validation accuracy across all epochs is 0.8856

6 Trial model - Regularisation l2, Gradient clipping and 70 epochs¶

From above trial model, number of epochs for robust fit is approximately 70.

In [0]:
trial_06 = keras.models.Sequential([
keras.layers.Dense(256, activation="relu",input_shape=[28*28],kernel_regularizer=keras.regularizers.l2(0.001)),
keras.layers.Dense(256, activation="relu",kernel_regularizer=keras.regularizers.l2(0.001)),
keras.layers.Dense(10, activation="softmax")
])

trial_06.compile(optimizer=optimizers.Adam(lr=0.001, clipnorm=1.0),
              loss='categorical_crossentropy',
              metrics=['accuracy'])


history_trial_06 = trial_06.fit(train_dataset,
                    epochs = 70,
                    validation_data=val_dataset,
                    callbacks=[tensorboard])

#Evaluating model over training and validation dataset
acc = history_trial_06.history['accuracy']
val_acc = history_trial_06.history['val_accuracy']
loss = history_trial_06.history['loss']
val_loss = history_trial_06.history['val_loss']

print("Average training accuracy across all epochs is",format(round(sum(acc)/len(acc),4)))
print("Average validation accuracy across all epochs is",format(round(sum(val_acc)/len(val_acc),4)))


#Plotting training and validation loss with number of epochs
plt.figure(figsize=(5, 5))
epochs = range(1, len(loss) + 1)
plt.plot(epochs, loss, 'bo', label='Training loss')
plt.plot(epochs, val_loss, 'b', label='Validation loss', color = 'red')
plt.title('Training and validation loss')
plt.xlabel('Epochs')
plt.ylabel('Loss')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

#Plotting training and validation accuracy with number of epochs
plt.figure(figsize=(5, 5))
epochs = range(1, len(acc) + 1)
plt.plot(epochs, acc, 'bo', label='Training accuracy')
plt.plot(epochs, val_acc, 'b', label='Validation accuracy', color = 'red')
plt.title('Training and validation accuracy')
plt.xlabel('Epochs')
plt.ylabel('Accruacy')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

Average training accuracy across all epochs is 0.9076
Average validation accuracy across all epochs is 0.89

1. Which configuration achieved the best test accuracy?¶

None of the combination gave robust fit. However, trial_06 model was better than other models.It seems Convulation2D layers should be tried for the given data.

2. Which setting had the most impact and which one had the least impact?¶

trial_06 model with l2 regulizer, Adam optimizer with gradient clipping was best and trial_03 model with 512 units, dropout 0.2, RMSprop with learning rate 0.01 was least impressive.
